URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS256077836	2021-03-30 17:31:48.868284	7149	species	Least Bittern	Ixobrychus exilis			2					United States	US	Michigan	US-MI	Barry	US-MI-015	US-MI_1655	23			Barry SGA--Fish Lake Unit	L1570666	H	42.5450241	-85.4912949	2014-05-24	08:40:00	obsr281935	S18535384	Traveling	P22	EBIRD	180	3.862		2	1	G911885	0	1	0		Circled Fish Lake by kayak.	Location: 80 yards north of where the boat launch channel meets the lake.  Heard one bird calling: "ko-ko-ko-ko" Stayed in the area for 20 minutes imitating the call with our voices.  The bird kept calling back. Saw nothing.  After 15 minutes a second bird landed in cattails 20 yards to our left.  We could see it was a bittern or heron.  The neck was streaked brown against a cream background.  It was about the size of a Green heron.  The crown was dark - almost black, the back was also dark and the nape of the neck was a rusty red-brown color.  Flanks were buffy, almost a warm orange-brown.  Bill was yellow, eye was yellow and there was red at the base of the bill.  This bird flew and landed near the unseen calling bird.  We could see one of the bitterns, sometimes two, deep in the cattails, walking about.  One was tugging at dead vegetation as if constructing a nest.

URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS266733679	2018-08-05 13:50:42	7149	species	Least Bittern	Ixobrychus exilis			8					United States	US	Michigan	US-MI	Bay	US-MI-017	US-MI_1628				Nayanquing Point SWA	L577756	H	43.7742237	-83.9376283	2014-08-04	07:00:00	obsr358645	S19361680	Traveling	P22	EBIRD	120	0.402		2	0		0	1	1		The following observations were made on or near the observation tower at the end of Tower Beach Road.	Very small heron-like bird; over-all chestnut-colored with vertical striping on underside of neck.  Dark crown and wings with contrasting chestnut-colored wing coverts.    Most seen at very close range and for surprisingly long periods.  Initially, four birds were counted just east of the tower; the count was difficult to make as the birds (adults and juveniles) were moving back and forth continuously.   The actual number may have been higher - four were counted individually at nearly the same time, however.  Three more (seen from the tower) were counted in widely separated areas to the west and south of the tower.   The last was observed 1/4 mile south of the tower.

The habitat here is good with the large cattail marsh and a mix of open water with dense vegetation and deeper water. Two birds called continuously from the vegetation for a few minutes. One was very close to the canoe launch and the other was directly east towards the viewing platform. I did not see the birds, only heard the calls. Pied-billed grebes have a rhythmic kow, kow, kow, but it louder and  increases in tempo and volume and other birds found in the marsh, mainly Sora and Virginia Rail do not make a similar call.

Fantastic find by Jake Hill. Very small heron-like bird (smaller than green heron). Dark cap and upperparts .Buffy face and underparts. Diagnostic buffy wing patches seen in flight. URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS210103589	2018-08-06 20:04:35	7149	species	Least Bittern	Ixobrychus exilis			1					United States	US	Michigan	US-MI	Macomb	US-MI-099		23			Lake St. Clair Metropark (Metro Beach Metropark)	L388494	H	42.5796301	-82.8032684	2013-09-07	09:58:00	obsr267922	S15113368	Traveling	P22	EBIRD	90	3.219		6	1	G689003	0	1	1			Photographed by Tom Heatley -We had a amazing time this morning at the South Marsh at Lake St. Clair Metro Park.  While looking for the Virginia Rail which has been spotted in the marsh for several weeks, we saw, at the same time in the same area, the Virginia Rail, Green Heron, Sora and Least Bittern.  We were all shocked and amazed!  The Least Bittern was a small bittern, several inches smaller and slimmer than the Green Heron, but larger than the Rail and the Sora.  The Bittern had a long pale yellow bill, a black cap on head, a black eye ring, yellowish/greenish legs, yellowish on the back of the neck, but the most distinctive marking were the long pale stripes on the neck.  Just an amazing opportunity to compare all four of these marsh birds, lurking around the cattails at the same time.

I am very familiar with this call year-round in Florida but was ready to dismiss it in light of the birds rarity at this season, but when I heard it again I felt it was worth reporting. Might be an injured bird unable to migrate.

We likely walked past this bird in the holding pond on our way out on the dike, but on our way back it flushed when we happened to stop and stand within 10 feet of it.  We got a clear prolonged look at the Heron when it flushed and  flew south through the bushes, and across the grasses to the distant cattail section.  This little brown Heron was too small for a Green Heron, and the wings clearly had identifying brown buff patches.  The double clincher in identification was the sweet, low cooing sound the bird made as it flew away from us.

Mouillee SGA	L248057	H	42.0146112	-83.2001495	2011-06-18	07:00:00	obsr218010	S42604934	Traveling	P22	EBIRD	180	9.656		1	0		0	1	0		A trip to Pt. Mouillee always carries the anticipation of seeing rare or casual bird species.  So much so that its easy to overlook the more common 'locals' that are here breeding and raising young.  Today, the birding was slow, so I had time to focus my efforts not only on the local birds, but also on some of resident insects.

Its "evasion flight" was quite erratic--eventually it went higher and flew out of sight (behind trees) at the far end of the marsh. Lighting was not good (cloudy, into east at 11am), so did not pick up color patterns. Flight was dainty, not like the bulkier Am. Bittern. In fact, the wing beat was more delicate, wings pointier, reminding me in some ways of a tern. Size was key--this seemed barely bigger than the blackbirds chasing it.

URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS267127504	2021-04-01 08:07:48.619151	7149	species	Least Bittern	Ixobrychus exilis			1	H 	C2	H 	Unknown Sex and Age (1)	United States	US	Michigan	US-MI	Washtenaw	US-MI-161		23			Matthaei Botanical Gardens	L492256	H	42.3007381	-83.6628628	2014-08-09	15:27:00	obsr203883	S19380226	Traveling	P22	EBIRD	28	0.161		1	1		0	1	0			Heard only. Sorry for the late post. Bird called once (typical 6 or 7 note vocalization: uh uh uh uh uh uh. I was so surprised at hearing it that I discounted it as wishful thinking. In talking to Roger Wykes the following afternoon, he told me that he had heard the same vocalization when he went to try for the BCNH an hour after I had seen it. He had similarly discounted the LEBI sound as it only called once. Since we both heard it an hour apart, we decided the little bugger must have indeed been a LEBI and had called once for each of us. Call came from southeast corner of big pond from dense cattails.

URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS508193474	2021-03-30 18:06:43.3116	7149	species	Least Bittern	Ixobrychus exilis			1					United States	US	Michigan	US-MI	Washtenaw	US-MI-161		23			Wood Duck Bayou	L1517269	P	42.3165000	-83.7848028	2017-06-04	12:00:00	obsr126012	S37390290	Stationary	P21	EBIRD	420			1	0		0	1	0		Day spent enjoying sounds and activities of local nesting species in and around yard.	Unexpected new yard bird calling persistently from cattails along river edge.  Have noted the song for the past four days, but was not positive of the ID.  After listening to at least a dozen recordings of the song of this species, I feel 98% confident  of the ID.  I have not glimpsed the birds as it is always deep in the cattails. Song is a soft, melodious "coo coo coo" as three of four syllables in continuous utterance. Checking various online sound libraries I found there are many varying dialects of this song, but they vary in tonality, not cadence or duration. The local bird seems to be more dove-like and less emphatic and coars than many ot the sound library recordings. I assume it is the male calling and possibly defining territory, but it may be a futile effort to attract a female to what seems like sub-marginal habitat. The bird calls thorughout the day, but most often in the morning before 10 am and evening after 6 pm.
